    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you for this! I'll be honest, this proof just feels above my pay-grade, especially the induction.  <br>\nBut I'm positive I'll run into more puzzles like this. If I've finished the tutorial project and I've just started <em>Mathematics in Lean</em>,  any suggestions for what I should start reading to get a better grasp on induction...?    Should I try jumping to the chapters on Induction in <em>TPIL</em>? Do I just need to open p. 1 of <em>TPIL</em> and start making my way through?</p>",
        "id": 218509886,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew  Souther",
        "timestamp": 1606877663
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I learnt a lot about induction by trying to prove basic facts about lists, for example that the reverae of the reverse of a list is itself. I spent some time translating parts of Coq's \"software foundations\" book into Lean.</p>",
        "id": 218530846,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1606900528
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However, are you sure that this proof is above your pay grade? It is a relatively straightforward translation of a slightly sneaky maths proof into lean. It's been well-compactified but that's just Mario's style. Can you prove it by indication on the size of S on paper? If you can't then the problem is not the Lean. The proof is quite different from the one I was suggesting.</p>",
        "id": 218531384,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1606900857
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The <code>replace</code> line and all the concise <code>obtain</code> statements scared me at first, but I've played around trying to copy that style in other proofs, and you're right that it's not so bad. I see it's really just a proof by cases,  and I think I do understand the pen-and-paper version of what Mario has done here. </p>\n<p>I have a few more concrete questions about the proof though, if anyone has the chance: <br>\n--What exactly is the <code>classical</code> line doing here?<br>\n--Can someone help unpack what's going on here in the induction line:  <code>(by rintro ⟨_, ⟨⟩⟩) </code></p>\n<p>I understand that you need to feed <code>finset.induction_on</code> three things:  a finset, a proof that a proposition is true for the empty finset, and a proof that  if it's true for some given finset, it's also true for the union of that finset and one more element. Mario has supplied S for the first term and left the third term blank to prove it later. But how does that second proof work?</p>",
        "id": 218592173,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew  Souther",
        "timestamp": 1606930792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>classical</code> -- remove it and see what happens! <code>finset</code> is quite constructive, the induction function needs an algorithm to figure out whether two terms of type <code>sigma</code> are equal. <code>classical</code> says \"sure there exists an algorithm, I'm not going to tell it you, but you're not going to actually ask what it is\".</p>",
        "id": 218603861,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1606935890
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The <code>rintro</code> line -- here it is, expanded out.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code>  <span class=\"n\">refine</span> <span class=\"n\">finset.induction_on</span> <span class=\"n\">S</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"n\">hS</span> <span class=\"n\">hR</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"c1\">-- { rintro ⟨_, ⟨⟩⟩ },</span>\n  <span class=\"o\">{</span> <span class=\"n\">intro</span> <span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n    <span class=\"n\">cases</span> <span class=\"n\">h</span> <span class=\"k\">with</span> <span class=\"n\">s</span> <span class=\"n\">h2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n    <span class=\"c1\">-- h2: s ∈ ∅</span>\n    <span class=\"n\">cases</span> <span class=\"n\">h2</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"c1\">-- no cases!</span>\n  <span class=\"o\">},</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 218604640,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1606936306
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>About the <code>rintro</code> line -- I guess it's just false that <code>s ∈ ∅</code>, so it's sort of an <em>ex falso quodlibet</em>  situation? <br>\nAbout <code>classical</code>-- If I remove it,  I see  Lean isn't convinced that this is true: <code>[decidable_eq σ]</code>.  I also see on mathlib that <code>finset.induction_on</code> implicitly needs a term like this. I guess this term tells us \"there exists an algorithm to determine whether two terms of type  σ are equal.\" </p>\n<p>I still don't really understand the mechanics of why <code>finset.induction_on</code> needs this though, but again maybe I would benefit from a bit more reading on induction.</p>",
        "id": 218615951,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew  Souther",
        "timestamp": 1606941483
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>finset.induction_on</code> needs <code>decidable_eq</code> because <code>insert</code> appears in the theorem statement</p>",
        "id": 218622383,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1606944566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and <code>insert</code> uses the <code>decidable_eq</code> proof in its definition</p>",
        "id": 218622415,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1606944589
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It might be nice to make a variation on <code>finset.induction_on</code> using <code>finset.cons</code> instead to avoid the assumption</p>",
        "id": 218622517,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1606944628
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>finset</code>s are implemented constructively in Lean, meaning that lean carries around a list which contains every element of the finset exactly once. So you can't really do anything useful with a finset like adding an element to it without an algorithm for knowing whether the element is in the set already. Because I'm only interested in proving theorems about finsets rather than actually using them to compute stuff, I just switch on <code>classical</code> and this makes the problem go away. Then finsets become nonconstructive in the sense that if I'm trying to compute an explicit finset I might be in trouble, but if I just want to prove theorems about them I'm still fine. To give an example of what the problem is, lean has a computable function <code>finset.card</code> which is supposed to return the size of a finset, but if you ran it on the finset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><msub><mo>∑</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>6</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{\\sum_{n\\geq1}n^{-2},\\pi^2/6\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.208997em;vertical-align:-0.39488900000000005em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:-0.0000050000000000050004em;\">∑</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15139799999999992em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.40029em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">≥</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.39488900000000005em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> you'd be asking lean to figure out whether the sum is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>6</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi^2/6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.064108em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\">6</span></span></span></span> or not, and this is a tricky little theorem rather than something a computer can do automatically.</p>",
        "id": 218623817,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1606945249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's subtle, but it makes sense --  thank you both.  Interesting that <code>insert</code>  is the culprit.</p>",
